            <img src="puran_poli.jpg" alt="Puran Poli">
            <div class="dish-info">
                <h2>Puran Poli</h2>
                <h3>Subheading</h3>
                <p>Puran Poli is a traditional Indian flatbread, especially popular in Maharashtra and Karnataka, known for
                    its delicious sweet filling. Made during festivals like Holi and Gudi Padwa, this delectable dish
                    features a dough made from wheat flour, which is rolled out and filled with a mixture of chana dal
                    (split chickpeas), jaggery, and cardamom. The combination is then expertly folded and cooked on a hot
                    griddle until golden brown. Puran Polis often served with a dollop of ghee or milk, enhancing its
                    rich flavor. This sweet treat not only satisfies the taste buds but also symbolizes the joy of
                    celebration and the warmth of home-cooked meals, making it a cherished part of Indian culinary
                    heritage.</p>
                <a href="#" class="recipe-button">Recipe</a>
            </div>
        </div>
        <div class="dish-card">
            <img src="vada_pav.jpg" alt="V ada Pav">
            <div class="dish-info">
                <h2>Vada Pav</h2>
                <h3>The Perfect Blend of Spices and Comfort</h3>
                <p>Vada Pav is a beloved street food originating from Mumbai, often referred to as the city's signature
                    snack. This delicious dish consists of a spiced potato patty, known as vada, encased in a soft bread
                    roll called pav. The potato filling is seasoned with garlic, green chilies, and various spices, creating
                    a flavorful bite. Typically served with chutneys—like green chutney and sweet tamarind
                    chutney—alongside fried green chilies, Vada Pav is both a filling snack and a quick meal. Its
                    popularity extends beyond Mumbai, symbolizing the vibrant street food culture of India. With its
                    unique blend of textures and flavors, Vada Pav captures the essence of urban culinary innovation and
                    the joy of communal dining.</p>
                <a href="#" class="recipe-button">Recipe</a>
            </div>
        </div>
        <div class="dish-card">
            <img src="bhakri.jpg" alt="Bhakri">
            <div class="dish-info">
                <h2>Bhakri</h2>
                <h3>A Rustic Delight from Western India</h3>
                <p>Bhakri is a traditional Indian flatbread, particularly cherished in Maharashtra and Gujarat. Made from
                    whole wheat, jowar (sorghum), or bajra (pearl millet) flour, this unleavened bread is known for its
                    hearty and wholesome characteristics. The preparation involves mixing the flour with water to form a
                    dough, which is then hand-rolled and cooked on a hot griddle or clay stove until it develops a slightly
                    crispier exterior and a soft interior. Bhakri is often enjoyed with spicy chutneys, curries, or ghee,
                    making it a versatile accompaniment to various meals. Its rustic flavor and texture reflect the
                    agricultural heritage of the region, and it serves as a symbol of comfort food, celebrating the
                    simplicity and richness of traditional Indian cuisine.</p>
                <a href="#" class="recipe-button">Recipe</a>
            </div>
        </div>
        <div class="dish-card">
            <img src="modak.jpg" alt="Modak">
            <div class="dish-info">
                <h2>Modak</h2>
                <h3>Divine Sweet Treat from Maharashtra</h3>
                <p>Modak is a traditional Indian sweet, especially popular in Maharashtra, celebrated as a favorite
                    offering to Lord Ganesha during festivals like Ganesh Chaturthi. These delightful dumplings are
                    made from rice flour or wheat flour and are typically filled with a sweet mixture of grated coconut
                    and jaggery, flavored with cardamom. The process of shaping modaks is an art in itself, as they are
                    carefully crafted into a distinctive conical shape, symbolizing a modak (pleat). Steamed or fried,
                    modaks are not only a treat for the palate but also carry deep cultural significance, representing
                    abundance and joy. Their exquisite taste and beautiful presentation make modaks a cherished
                    delicacy, reflecting the rich culinary traditions of India.</p>
                <a href="#" class="recipe-button">Recipe</a>
            </div>
        </div>
        <div class="dish-card">
            <img src="misal_pav.jpg" alt="Misal Pav">
            <div class="dish-info">
                <h2>Misal Pav</h2>
                <h3>The Spicy Street Food Marvel of Maharashtra</h3>
                <p>Misal Pav is a renowned street food dish from Maharashtra, celebrated for its bold flavors and vibrant
                    presentation. This spicy curry is made from a mixture of sprouted lentils, typically matki (moth
                    beans), cooked with an array of spices, onions, and tomatoes. The dish is topped with crunchy
                    farsan (savory snacks), chopped onions, and fresh coriander, creating a delightful contrast in textures.
                    Served alongside soft bread rolls known as pav, Misal Pav offers a hearty and fulfilling meal. It
                    is often enjoyed with a squeeze of lime and a side of buttermilk, enhancing its refreshing taste. This
                    dish not only showcases the rich culinary heritage of Maharashtra but also embodies the spirit of
                    communal eating, making it a favorite among food lovers.</p>
                <a href="#" class="recipe-button">Recipe</a>
            </div>
